      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "perf(memory): batch memory embeddings across files",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- Problem: batch memory indexing submitted provider batch jobs one file at a time, so many small memory and session files underfilled providers that support large batch jobs.\n- Solution: built-in provider runtimes explicitly opt into source-wide batching; custom runtimes without that opt-in keep the previous per-file `batchEmbed` contract.\n- What changed: `manager-embedding-ops.ts` only source-wide batches runtimes with `sourceWideBatchEmbed: true`, flushes each source-wide group at 1024 files or 4096 chunks, and keeps per-file writes; OpenAI, Gemini, and Voyage opt in explicitly.\n- What did NOT change: FTS-only indexing, configured cache behavior, stale-file pruning, multimodal fallbacks, and third-party provider runtimes without opt-in remain on existing per-file paths.\n\nFixes #88009\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- **Behavior or issue addressed:** built-in provider runtimes can batch small dirty memory and session files together by source, while unopted custom runtimes still receive one file's chunks per `batchEmbed` call.\n- **Real environment tested:** Linux worktree at `pr-88238-redlabels`, Node 22, production memory manager path with local test provider runtimes covering source-wide opt-in and no-opt-in compatibility.\n- **Exact steps or command run after this patch:**\n\n  ```bash\n  node --import tsx --input-type=module <<'JS'\n  import fs from \"node:fs/promises\";\n  import os from \"node:os\";\n  import path from \"node:path\";\n  import { clearMemoryEmbeddingProviders, registerMemoryEmbeddingProvider } from \"openclaw/plugin-sdk/memory-core-host-engine-embeddings\";\n  import { closeAllMemorySearchManagers, getMemorySearchManager } from \"./extensions/memory-core/src/memory/index.ts\";\n\n  const root = await fs.mkdtemp(path.join(os.tmpdir(), \"openclaw-memory-batch-proof-\"));\n  const workspace = path.join(root, \"workspace\");\n  const memoryDir = path.join(workspace, \"memory\");\n  await fs.mkdir(memoryDir, { recursive: true });\n  await fs.writeFile(path.join(memoryDir, \"a.md\"), \"# A\\nAlpha memory line.\", \"utf-8\");\n  await fs.writeFile(path.join(memoryDir, \"b.md\"), \"# B\\nBeta memory line.\", \"utf-8\");\n  await fs.writeFile(path.join(memoryDir, \"c.md\"), \"# C\\nGamma memory line.\", \"utf-8\");\n\n  const batchSubmissions = [];\n  const vectorFor = (text) => [text.includes(\"Alpha\") ? 1 : 0, text.includes(\"Beta\") ? 1 : 0, text.includes(\"Gamma\") ? 1 : 0];\n  clearMemoryEmbeddingProviders();\n  registerMemoryEmbeddingProvider({\n    id: \"proof-batch\",\n    defaultModel: \"proof-embed\",\n    transport: \"remote\",\n    create: async () => ({\n      provider: {\n        id: \"proof-batch\",\n        model: \"proof-embed\",\n        embedQuery: async (text) => vectorFor(text),\n        embedBatch: async (texts) => texts.map(vectorFor),\n      },\n      runtime: {\n        id: \"proof-batch\",\n        sourceWideBatchEmbed: true,\n        batchEmbed: async ({ chunks }) => {\n          batchSubmissions.push(chunks.map((chunk) => chunk.text));\n          return chunks.map((chunk) => vectorFor(chunk.text));\n        },\n      },\n    }),\n  });\n\n  const result = await getMemorySearchManager({ cfg: { agents: { defaults: { workspace, memorySearch: { provider: \"proof-batch\", model: \"proof-embed\", store: { path: path.join(workspace, \"index.sqlite\"), vector: { enabled: false } }, chunking: { tokens: 4000, overlap: 0 }, sync: { watch: false, onSessionStart: false, onSearch: false }, remote: { nonBatchConcurrency: 1, batch: { enabled: true, wait: true, concurrency: 2, pollIntervalMs: 0, timeoutMinutes: 1 } } } }, list: [{ id: \"main\", default: true }] } }, agentId: \"main\" });\n  await result.manager.sync({ reason: \"proof\" });\n  const status = result.manager.status();\n  console.log(JSON.stringify({ filesCreated: [\"a.md\", \"b.md\", \"c.md\"], batchSubmissionCount: batchSubmissions.length, batchSubmissionSizes: batchSubmissions.map((items) => items.length), batchedTexts: batchSubmissions[0], indexedFiles: status.files, indexedChunks: status.chunks, batchStatus: status.batch }, null, 2));\n  await closeAllMemorySearchManagers();\n  clearMemoryEmbeddingProviders();\n  await fs.rm(root, { recursive: true, force: true });\n  JS\n  ```\n\n- **Evidence after fix:** Copied terminal console output from the command above:\n\n  ```json\n  {\n    \"filesCreated\": [\n      \"a.md\",\n      \"b.md\",\n      \"c.md\"\n    ],\n    \"batchSubmissionCount\": 1,\n    \"batchSubmissionSizes\": [\n      3\n    ],\n    \"batchedTexts\": [\n      \"# A\\nAlpha memory line.\",\n      \"# B\\nBeta memory line.\",\n      \"# C\\nGamma memory line.\"\n    ],\n    \"indexedFiles\": 3,\n    \"indexedChunks\": 3,\n    \"batchStatus\": {\n      \"enabled\": true,\n      \"failures\": 0,\n      \"limit\": 2,\n      \"wait\": true,\n      \"concurrency\": 2,\n      \"pollIntervalMs\": 0,\n      \"timeoutMs\": 60000\n    }\n  }\n  ```\n\n- **Observed result after fix:** an opted-in runtime batches dirty memory files together, forced CLI-style memory+sessions indexing submits one memory batch and one session batch, custom runtimes without opt-in stay per-file, and source-wide groups are bounded at 1024 files or 4096 chunks so the 833-file maintainer repro fits in one runtime batch.\n- **What was not tested:** a live remote embedding provider batch job; the proof uses the production memory manager and provider-runtime batch seam with a local provider adapter to avoid external credentials.\n\n## Regression Test Plan\n\n- Coverage level: extension unit/integration tests plus direct production-path proof.\n- Target test file: `extensions/memory-core/src/memory/index.test.ts`.\n- Scenario locked in: opted-in dirty memory files batch together, unopted custom runtimes stay per-file, source-wide memory batches are bounded at 1024 files / 4096 chunks, and forced CLI-style memory+sessions indexing batches session transcripts across files as a single source batch.\n- Why this is the smallest reliable guardrail: it exercises the real sync/index manager path where dirty files are collected and provider runtime batch submission is invoked.\n\n## Verification\n\n```bash\nnode scripts/run-vitest.mjs extensions/memory-core/src/memory/index.test.ts -t \"batches\"\npnpm test:extension memory-core\npnpm tsgo:extensions\npnpm tsgo:test:extensions\npnpm check:changed\ngit diff --check\n```\n\nLatest local results:\n\n```text\nnode scripts/run-vitest.mjs extensions/memory-core/src/memory/index.test.ts -t \"batches\"\nTest Files 1 passed (1)\nTests 4 passed | 20 skipped (24)\n\npnpm test:extension memory-core\nTest Files 59 passed (59)\nTests 766 passed (766)\n\npnpm check:changed\nlanes=core, coreTests, extensions, extensionTests\nall changed gates completed successfully\n```\n\n## Root Cause\n\n- Root cause: memory and session sync built one task per dirty file and each task called `indexFile`, so runtime `batchEmbed` only ever received chunks from that one file.\n- Missing detection / guardrail: existing tests verified batching multiple chunks already passed together, but not source-wide opt-in compatibility, bounded source-wide grouping, or forced memory+session indexing.\n",
